public" interests. In the process she illuminates the connections between aesthetic, sexual, and social formations in modern life—between modernity's disruptive, "queer" desires and their unfolding in an increasingly rationalized society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aDandyism in literature. 0aHomosexuality and literature. 0aQueer theory. 4aGender and Sexuality : Lesbian / Gay Studies. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aLiterature : Literary Theory. 4aPolitics and Law : Marxism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / LGBT.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143842738640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438427386423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438427386/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles